	<h4 align="left">A Look at the Martingale Strategy</h4>
	<p align="left">
		Even money bets have inspired many players over the years to 
		attempt to beat the game by using strategies like the Martingale betting strategy.
		where a player at least doubles the bet after every loss, so that the first win would recover 
		all previous losses, plus win a profit. The problem with this 
		strategy is that, remembering that past results do not affect the future, it is possible
		for the player to lose so many times in a row, that the player, doubling and redoubling 
		his bets, either runs out of money or their bet becomes to high since the table will have a max bet.
	</p>
	<p align="left">
		Martingale strategies came about during the 18th century in France.
		The simplest strategy was designed where a player wins his stake if 
		a coin comes up heads, and loses if tails. The strategy had the gambler double
		his bet after every loss, so that the first win would recover all previous losses plus win a 
		profit. Now a player with infinite wealth will, almost surely, 
		eventually flip heads, so the Martingale strategy was seen as full-proof. Of course, nobody has 
		infinite wealth, so the increase in bets would eventually bankrupt the player.
	</p>
	<p align="left">
		So bottom line?  Use, but be preparred to lose all your money quickly.  If you win early, 
		don't be greedy, just take your winnings and go to dinner.
	</p>
