	<h4 align="left">Biased Wheels Payed Big</h4>
	<p align="left">
		In the early 90s, Gonzalo Garcia-Pelayo thought that roulette wheels were not perfectly random (meaning imperfections in the wheel 			itslef).  He though by recording the results and analysing them with a computer, he could gain an edge on the house
		by predicting that certain numbers were more likely to occur next than the 1-in-36 odds offered by the 
		house suggested. He did this at the Casino de Madrid in Madrid, Spain, winning 600,000 euros in a single 
		day, and one million euros overall. The casino too legal action, but was unsuccessful, the court ruled that the casino 
		should simply fix their wheels.
	</p>
	<p align="left">
		Today, casinos monitor the performance of their wheels, rebalance and 
		realign them to try and keep the result perfectly random (every number having an equal percentage of possibly coming up).
	</p>
	<p align="left">
		A new wheel, designed by George Melas, was called "low-profile" because the number pockets reduced in depth, and various other design 			modifications caused the ball to descend in a gradual approach to a number. In 1986, the professional gambling team headed by 
		Billy Walters won 3.8 million dollars using this analysis system on an old wheel that was in place at the Golden Nugget in Atlantic 			City.  Virtually every casino in the world took note, and in 12 months they switched to the new low-profile roulette wheel.
	</p>
